SALMONELLOSIS, IMPORTED MEAT, 2005 - SWEDEN EX ITALY (02): BACKGROUND
***********************************************
A ProMED-mail post
<http://www.promedmail.org>
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
<http://www.isid.org>
Date: Sun 12 Feb 2006
From: Steve Berger <mberger@post.tau.ac.il>
Source: GideonOnline [edited]
<http://www.GideonOnline.com>

A chronology of some recent cross-border salmonellosis outbreaks
-----------------------------------------------
1973 to 1974 - An outbreak (80 cases in the USA and 39 in Canada) of
serotype Eastborne infection was caused by contaminated chocolate.
1995 - An outbreak (27 cases in the UK) of serotype Agona infection
was caused by a savory snack imported from Israel.
1997 - An outbreak (242 cases, approximate) in the USA and Finland of
serotype Stanley infection was traced to alfalfa sprouts.
1997 - An outbreak of serotype Livingstone infection was reported in
Western Europe; several of the cases were acquired abroad, notably in Tunisia.
1998 - Outbreaks of serotype Blockley infection were reported in
Germany, Austria, Belgium, Sweden, Finland and the UK, with smoked
eel implicated in some countries.
1999 - An outbreak (275 cases) of _Salmonella paratyphi_ B infection
was reported among European tourists who visited Turkey during the
summer of 1999.
2000 - Outbreaks of serotype Typhimurium DT204b infection (total 396
cases) which may have been related occurred in Iceland, England and
Wales, the Netherlands, Scotland and Germany. Contaminated lettuce
was implicated.
2000 to 2001 - An outbreak (168 cases, total) of serotype Enteritidis
phage type 30 infection (157 cases in Canada, 11 in the USA) was
caused by contaminated raw almonds.
2001 - Outbreaks of serotype Typhimurium DT 104 infection caused by a
batch of imported Turkish halvah were reported in Australia and
Sweden. Contaminated halvah was also identified in Germany, Norway and the UK.
2001 - An outbreak of serotype Stanley infection in Australia and
Canada was associated with contaminated peanuts imported from China.
2001 - An outbreak of serotype Oranienburg due to contaminated German
chocolate affected several European countries.
2001 - An outbreak (301 cases) of serotype Enteritidis infection was
reported among Scandinavian tourists returning from Crete and
Karpathos. The probable source was contaminated poultry.
2003 - Outbreaks of serotype Montivideo infection in Australia and
New Zealand were caused by contaminated sesame seed products (Tahini
and Halva) imported from Egypt and Lebanon.
2004 - Raw almonds contaminated with serotype Enteritidis were
recalled by the manufacturer from China, Taiwan, Democratic Republic
of Korea, France, Italy, Japan, Malaysia, Mexico and the UK.
2004 - Ruccola lettuce contaminated with serotype Thompson was
identified in Norway, Sweden and the UK.
2005 - An outbreak (5 cases, total) of serotype Thompson infection (3
cases in Canada and 2 in the USA) was caused by handling contaminated
pet treats.
2005 - An outbreak (48 cases, total) of serotype Stourbridge
infection in Sweden (6 cases), Switzerland (3), Germany (2), Austria
(5), UK (3) and France (27) was caused by unpasteurized French soft cheese.
2005 - An outbreak (178 cases) of serotype Goldcoast infection in
Majorca affected tourists from Scotland (37), Ireland (6), Sweden
(6), Norway (8), Denmark (3), Germany (20) and Finland (4).
2005 - An outbreak (22 cases) of serotype Typhimurum DT104 infection
in Denmark was caused by raw beef carpaccio imported from Italy.
--
Dr. Steve Berger
Geographic Medicine
Tel Aviv Medical Center
<mberger@post.tau.ac.il>
